In Michigan, there are a number of murder victims, in the category of [[unidentified decedent]]s, whose identities have yet to be determined.
==Chippewa County John Doe==
{{external media | align = | width = | image1 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/8365 Sketch] | image2 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/8366 Profile] | image3 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/9084 Belongings] | image4 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/9085 Keys] }}
On November 13, 1966, the decomposed body of a male was found in the [[Hiawatha National Forest]] in [[Trout Lake, Michigan|Trout Lake]], Chippewa County, Michigan. The man's exact cause of death has not been released, but the nature was determined to have been murder. The victim was aged between nineteen and twenty-five, although he may have been up to thirty years old when he died. He was approximately {{convert|5|ft|10|in}} tall at a weight of {{convert|150|lb|kg}}. His hair was around {{convert|4|in|cm|spell=in}} long and was brown with a reddish tint. He was dressed in a tan shirt with jeans and had both American and Canadian currency in his shirt pocket, leading officers to believe he was of Canadian nationality. Additionally, he was found near the border of the Canadian province of [[Ontario]]. A gold and chrome-colored lighter and a set of five Canadian-style keys on a key ring, with the number "330" etched in it, were also found with the remains. The man's belongings and clothing no longer exist, as they were destroyed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 948UMMI|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/948ummi.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=December 27, 2014}}</ref> He is believed to have died approximately six months before his discovery.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 8378|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/8378|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=December 27, 2014|date=January 12, 2011}}</ref>
{{anchor|Wayne County Jane Doe (1987)}}
==Wayne County Jane Doe (1987)==
{{external media | align = | width = | image1 = [http://media2.wxyz.com/photo/2014/11/10/police-sketch-unsolved_1415647409025_9541348_ver1.0_640_480.png Sketch] }}
On February 10, 1987, the body of a young woman, aged 16 to 25 was located in a dump in [[Detroit]], Wayne County, Michigan. The victim was deceased less than two days and had been stabbed to death.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bodies exhumed at Plymouth cemetery by police for DNA testing|url=http://www.myfoxdetroit.com/story/27342968/2-bodies-being-exhumed-at-plymouth-cemetery|accessdate=November 18, 2014|publisher=[[WJBK-TV]]|location=Detroit|agency=Fox News|date=November 10, 2014}}</ref> She was approximately {{Convert|5|ft|5|in|m}} tall and weighed around {{convert|114|lb|kg}}. The victim had given birth eight weeks to one year prior and she was lactating.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 8272|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/8272|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=November 18, 2014|date=December 15, 2010}}</ref> A scar from an [[episiotomy]] was also found on her body. Her hair was brown with red and blond highlights and was styled with a long nape with various layers. She was slender, but had an athletic build and an O blood type. Her nails were painted with pink polish and she had brown or hazel eyes. A worn black bikini bottom was the only clothing she wore. Two rings were found on her left hand, one on her index finger and one on her ring finger, indicating she may have been married. She also had pierced ears.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1987|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMC/1184291/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref> Along with some other unidentified decedents from Detroit, the victim was exhumed in 2014 for additional examination.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Craig|first1=Kim|title=Police and federal investigators dig up bodies hoping DNA will help put names to unsolved deaths|url=http://www.wxyz.com/news/region/wayne-county/police-and-federal-investigators-dig-up-bodies-hoping-dna-will-help-put-names-to-unsolved-deaths|accessdate=November 18, 2014|publisher= [[WXYZ-TV]] |location= Detroit|agency=ABC News|date=November 10, 2014}}</ref>
==Berrien County Jane Doe== {{external media | align = | width = | image1 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/8425 3D reconstruction] | image2 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/129UFMI2.jpg Sketch] }} The remains of a woman were found on August 23, 1992 in [[New Buffalo, Michigan|New Buffalo]], Berrien County, Michigan. The victim was nude and between the ages of 65 and 75 when she was murdered. The victim was wrapped in a bed sheet, two garbage bags and a towel and left alongside a highway. Her hands were severed to prevent identification through fingerprint examination.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case file #2 Unidentified female 1992|url=http://www.bcsheriff.org/main/Casefile2Unidentifiedfemale1992|website=www.bcsheriff.org/|publisher=Berrien County Police Department|accessdate=December 4, 2014}}</ref> The victim was also missing her dentures, as she had no teeth. The body was at the scene for approximately two days, but she was killed four to seven days before. The woman may have been from a nursing home in Illinois or Indiana.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 129UFMI|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/129ufmi.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=December 4, 2014}}</ref> She was believed to have been five feet two inches tall at a weight of around 102 pounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 8224|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/8224|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=December 4, 2014|date=December 8, 2010}}</ref>
{{anchor|Highland Park Jane Doe}}
==Highland Park Jane Doe==
{{external media | align = | width = | image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1228681c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction] | image2 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1228681x1.jpg Second NCMEC reconstruction] | image3 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1228681x2.jpg Watch] }}
The body of a female between fifteen and twenty-five years old was located in an alley in [[Highland Park, Michigan|Highland Park]], Wayne County, Michigan on May 20, 1996. The victim's cause of death has not been disclosed, but is considered a homicide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unidentified Remains: Highland Park, MI|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/vicap/unidentified-persons/jane-doe-43/vicap-jane-doe-highland-park-mi-5-20-1996.pdf |format= PDF|publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]|accessdate=December 27, 2014}}</ref> The young woman weighed {{convert|191|lb|kg}} and was {{convert|5|ft|3|in|m}} tall. She is presumed to be a mix of white and African-American. Her hair was reddish-brown, curly and tied with a white bow in a ponytail. She wore a distinctive white shirt with yellow smiley faces, a white bra, white socks and black shoes, as well as a teddy-bear shaped wristwatch. Her eyes were brown, like her hair. The victim's teeth had three fillings and untreated decay, although none of them had been removed. She is also believed to have been a tobacco smoker. Other than this, she is believed to have been drug-free. She had O type blood and painted her nails, her fingernails were purple and her toenails were pink. Other distinguishing features included many freckles on her face and a scar under her right knee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1996|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1228681/1|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=December 27, 2014}}</ref> The victim also had pelvic inflammatory disease.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 11787|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/11787|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=December 27, 2014|date=November 19, 2013}}</ref>
{{anchor|Jack in the Box (murder victim)}}
=="Jack in the Box"== {{external media | align = | width = | image1 = [http://www.delayedjustice.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2008/05/jack_in_the_box-150x150.jpg Sketch] }} In the afternoon of May 8, 2002, the burned body of a white or Hispanic man was discovered in a wooded area of a blueberry field in [[Grand Haven, Michigan|Grand Haven]], Ottawa County, Michigan. The man was killed by blunt force trauma and was then set on fire after being transported to the area. He had extensive dental work, including a partial dental plate, crowns and restorations. However, they had not been performed within a decade before he died. It is believed that he received such care in the southern United States or Mexico. His clothing included a shirt originating from southern California, boxer shorts and a watch. He was {{convert|5|ft|6|in|m}} to {{convert|5|ft|7|in|m}} tall and was fairly healthy when he was alive. His remains were found in a footlocker that was then set on fire. A charred cushion, which was placed below the remains, was also found. Because of the size of the footlocker and the absence of disturbance to the surface of the earth, it is believed that more than one person was involved in disposing the corpse. Because it had rained the morning of the discovery, trace evidence at the scene was no longer available.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jack in the Box|url=http://www.delayedjustice.com/?page_id=10|website=delayedjustice.com|publisher=penULTIMATE, Ltd|accessdate=August 3, 2014|year=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jack In The Box|url=http://www.delayedjustice.com/?p=589|publisher=Delayed Justice|accessdate=August 3, 2014|date=July 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 1288UMMI|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/1288ummi.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=August 3, 2014}}</ref>
{{anchor|Wayne County Jane Doe (2005)}}
==Wayne County Jane Doe (2005)== [[File:Detroit, Michigan Jane Doe facial reconstruction.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Reconstruction of the 2005 Wayne County Jane Doe prior to losing her teeth.]]
{{external media | align = | width = | image1 = [http://mi.gov/images/Mummyphotos_004_148718_7.jpg 3D reconstruction] }}
On July 13, 2005, the severely deteriorated body of a 35- to 60-year-old woman was found naked inside an abandoned building in [[Detroit]], Michigan. The woman had extremely poor dentition, possibly due to [[methamphetamine]] use.<ref name="Detroit Jane Doe">{{cite web| title=Detroit Jane Doe| url=http://www.hellbeasts.com/?p=6274| accessdate=April 21, 2014| date=February 6, 2014}}</ref> However, the nails on the toes and fingers were well cared for. She had short [[auburn hair|auburn]] and grey hair; standing at approximately {{convert|5|ft|3|in}} tall. The skull was reconstructed twice, once with clay and the other by drawing.<ref name="Identification Sought: Jane Doe">{{cite web| title=Identification Sought: 'Jane Doe'| url=http://mi.gov/documents/JaneDoeFlyer_148714_7.pdf |format= PDF| accessdate=April 21, 2014}}</ref><ref name="mi.gov">{{cite web| title=MSP Forensic Artist to Release Facial Reconstruction Build upon Skull of Unidentified Remains| url=http://mi.gov/msp/0,1607,7-123-1586_1710-135001--,00.html| accessdate=April 21, 2014| date=January 26, 2006}}</ref><ref name="Case Report - NamUs UP # 7702">{{cite web| title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 7702| url=https://identifyus.org/cases/full_report/7702| accessdate=April 21, 2014| date=August 27, 2010}}</ref><ref name="Case File 410UFMI">{{cite web| title=Case File 410UFMI| url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/410ufmi.html| publisher=The Doe Network| accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>
{{anchor|Wayne County Jane Doe (2006)}}
==Wayne County Jane Doe (2006)== {{external media | align = | width = | image1 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/7259 3D reconstruction] }} An African-American woman of slender build, reported to be a [[prostitute]], was discovered around a week after her death on June 5, 2006. She had been [[strangulation|strangled]] and had also suffered [[Major trauma|trauma]] to the head.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unknown Black Female from Detroit|url=http://www.michigan.gov/msp/0,4643,7-123-1589_31786_54860_54861-237311--,00.html|publisher=Michigan State Police|accessdate=August 3, 2014}}</ref> She was between 20 and 30 years of age and had been left in a deserted building. The clothing she wore included a red T-shirt, a blue jacket decorated with flags and [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] shoes. One of her front teeth was missing; the oral care was not well performed. Shelley Brooks, a [[serial killer]], confessed to killing her and six other women and remains [[incarceration|incarcerated]] for the [[life sentence|rest of his life]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Jane Doe| url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/sites/default/files/Michigan%20Detroit%20Jane%20Doe%20June%202006%20FLYER.pdf |format= PDF| publisher=Wayne County Police Department| accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Wayne Michigan Jane Doe June 2006">{{cite web| title=Wayne Michigan Jane Doe June 2006| url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/WayneMichiganJaneDoeJune2006| accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Case File 73UFMI">{{cite web| title=Case File 73UFMI| url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/73ufmi.html| publisher=The Doe Network| accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Kearns">{{cite news| last=Kearns| first=Jeanne| title=Serial Killer Suspect, Shelly Andre Brooks Convicted in Detroit| url=http://voices.yahoo.com/serial-killer-suspect-shelly-andre-brooks-convicted-239075.html| accessdate=May 10, 2014| newspaper=Yahoo Voices| date=March 8, 2007}}</ref>
{{anchor|Wayne County Jane Doe (2009)}}
==Wayne County Jane Doe (2009)== [[File:Detroit Jane Doe facial reconstruction.jpg|thumb|150px|The Jane Doe found in Detroit in 2009]] The partially mummified remains of a woman were located in Detroit, Wayne County, Michigan on March 26, 2009 in an alley. The woman's cause of death is unknown, but she was found without clothing, which indicates homicide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Detroit, Michigan Jane Doe|url=http://www.hellbeasts.com/?p=6478|accessdate=October 14, 2014|date=March 8, 2014}}</ref> The victim was between 25 and 45 years old, standing around {{convert|4|ft|8|in|m}} tall. Because of the state of her body, her weight could not be estimated. The Jane Doe was deceased for approximately eight months. Judging by a wad of hair found at the scene, she may have had red or auburn hair when she was alive. Examining the woman's bones suggested that she had borne at least one child and had trauma to her back before she died, which likely caused her pain.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 8175|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/8175|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons Database]]|accessdate=October 14, 2014}}</ref>
