'''Louise Hunt''' is a British [[coroner]] who is currently HM Coroner for Birmingham and Solihull, and the first female ever to take up the role, preceded by eight male coroners before her.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/louise-hunt-birminghams-first-female-6868677|title=Louise Hunt: Birmingham's first female coroner |author=Catherine Lillington|date=24 March 2014|work=[[Birmingham Mail]]}}</ref>

Before becoming the coroner, the mother-of-two had left her hometown of [[Newcastle-under-Lyme]] for Birmingham at 18 and worked as a nurse at [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital Birmingham]], graduating with a law degree in 1992. She was appointed in 2013 on the resignation of Aidan Cotter OBE who had been in the role for little more than a decade. In the process, Louise became the first female coroner in Birmingham legal history.{{cn|date=February 2017}}

In 2016 she was asked by a campaign of bereaved families to resume the inquest into the [[Birmingham pub bombings]] of 1974.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/feb/10/birmingham-pub-bombings-victims-families-push-to-reopen-investigation|title=Birmingham pub bombings: victims' families push to reopen investigation|author=Owen Bowcott|work=[[the Guardian]]|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref>

